						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#143;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#132;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#161;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#171;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#161;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#139;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#132; (Kunoichi ni Chikai) is a game about ninjas in training. A &amp;quot;kunoichi&amp;quot; is a female ninja, and &amp;quot;kunoichi ni chikai&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;almost a kunoichi&amp;quot; - but you could also read it as &amp;quot;close to the ku&amp;quot;. But what's &amp;quot;ku&amp;quot;? It's a little pink token in the box! Use the powers of your kunoichi trainees to move them around in the grid and get closer to the &amp;quot;ku&amp;quot;!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;At the start of the game sixteen cards, one for each character, are laid out in a four by four grid. The players are dealt an equal number of cards, each corresponding to one of the ninjas. Each card has a different ability to move cards around, like &amp;quot;swap any card and the one two to the right and one down from it&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;slide any column up, wrapping around&amp;quot;. After each player has used all but one of their cards, the last card determines which ninja they get points for, with more points going to ninjas closer to the &amp;quot;ku&amp;quot;.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In order to win you'll have to use your powers to rearrange the grid while balancing that with holding on a character in a good position, even if they have good powers. You also have to be careful not to favor any character too obviously as other players can interrupt your plans.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Can you get close to the &amp;quot;ku&amp;quot; and finally become a full kunoichi?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
